Madrid districts

The end goal of this section is to create a map of Madrid’s districts coloring each district based on the average price per square meter we would have to pay should we want an appartment there.

We are going to approach to the problem incrementally, in the following steps:

  1. Load the data about Madrid’s average prices and the polygon’s signalling the bounds of Madrid’s districts.
  2. Load polygons in our map signalling the boundaries of the different Madrid’s districts.
  3. Color the polygons following a categorical variable based on the districts name.
  4. Add the data about the average prices in the different districts.
  5. Color the polygons following a numerical continuous scale based on the average prices.
  6. Color the polygons following a numerical continuous scale but turnng the variable discrete using quantiles.

0. Load the data

Average prices in the different Madrid districts

First, we are going to load the data about the average prices per square meter in the different districts in Madrid. This is contained in an excel file. Remember, save your notebook and the excel file to the same folder and then run the following code:

madrid_prices <- read_xlsx("madrid_district_prices.xlsx")

1. Load district polygons in the map signalling the boundaries of the different districts.

To do this and once the data is in sp format (see the previous point), the following code suffices.

# Initializes the map app and provides the necessary data
leaflet(mad_districts) %>%
  
  # Loads the basemap
  addTiles() %>%
  
  # Adds the polygons contained in map_districts
  addPolygons()

The above output is nice, but we may want to adjust the width of the boundaries between the districts or the colors. On top of that, we want the name of the district to be shown when hovering over each district with the mouse. Some basic adjustments of the parameters of this simple polygon map can be done as below.

leaflet(mad_districts) %>%
  
  # Loads the basemap
  addTiles() %>%
  
  # Loads the polygons
  addPolygons(
    
    # Adds thick line for polygon boundaries
    stroke = TRUE, 
    
    # Sets width value for polygon boundaries
    weight = 2, 
    
    # Changes default color of boundaries and fill
    color = "grey",
    
    # Defines a separate color to fill the polygons. Overrides the
    # argument color for the polygons (color is still used for the edges)
    # It is another kind of blue in HEX code)
    fillColor = "#a8efff", 
    
    # Adjusts the transparecy of the fill color of the polygons
    fillOpacity = 0.5,
    
    # Shows label when hovering over the districts
    # The variable name referes to the name of the district 
    # to be found in the dataframe mad_districts@data
    label = ~paste0("Distrito - ", name) 
    )

2. Color the polygons following a categorical variable based on the name of the district

2.1 Coloring the polygons

To add a qualitative color scale to match a categorical variable (such as the district name), we are going to use the function colorFactor, from the library leaflet.

Essentialy this function requires two arguments

  • palette: this argument specified the colors to map the data to. It can take one of several forms:
    • The name of a preset palette from the RColorBrewer package, e.g. "RdYlBu", "Accent", or "Greens". These scales can be found on this link. We will also see them how to add to them within R
    • The full name of a viridis palette: "viridis", "magma", "inferno", or "plasma". These can be found on this link
    • A character vector specifying colors, e.g. c("#000000", "#0000FF", "#FFFFFF"), topo.colors(10).
  • domain: tellls the color function the range of input values. We will pass NULL here and the palette function will infer the range everytime we use it in a map.

Since we have a categorical variable, the color scale we used must be focused on making the different categories distinct. For this, we want a qualitative scale, although a sequential scale can sometimes work or this. The differences between sequential, categorical and qualitative color scales are explained in notebook 03, which covers graph customization in ggplot. Refer to that notebook for the details.

We can use the function display.brewer.all() from the library RColorBrewer to examine the different kind of scales available from the RColorBrewer package as follows:

# Display sequential palettes to pick one among them
display.brewer.all(type = "seq")

# Display qualitative palettes to pick one among them
display.brewer.all(type = "qual")

Having a look at the alternatives, we decide to go with the qualitative scale "Set3" from the RColorBrewer package. The code below introduces changes to our previous graph to have the polygons colored following this scale

# Define a scale appropriate for a categorical variable
# with distinct colors. we pick the scale "Set3".
factpal <- colorFactor(palette = "Set3", domain = NULL)

map_categoricals <-
  
  leaflet(mad_districts) %>%
    
    # Loads the background map
    addTiles() %>%
    
    # Loads the polygons
    addPolygons(
      
      # Adds thick line for polygon boundaries
      stroke = TRUE, 
      
      # Sets width value for polygon boundaries
      weight = 2, 
      
      # Changes default color of boundaries and fill
      color = "grey",
      
      # Use the previously created color scale to fill the polygons
      # Note that name refers to the column name in mad_districts@data,
      # which signals the name of every district.
      fillColor =  ~factpal(name), 
      
      # Adjusts the transparecy of the fill color of the polygons
      fillOpacity = 0.7,
      
      # Shows label when hovering over the districts
      # The variable name referes to the name of the district 
      # to be found in the dataframe mad_districts@data
      label = ~paste0("Distrito - ", name) 
      )
Warning in RColorBrewer::brewer.pal(max(3, n), palette): n too large, allowed maximum for palette Set3 is 12
Returning the palette you asked for with that many colors
# Display the map
map_categoricals

2.2 Adding a legend (optional)

We may now also add a legend if we want to, although it may not be very helpful when the colors are so close to each other. The point of using these scales is to make the polygons easily discernible when navigating the map, the legend does not help much here.

It is much more useful to receive a feedback message with the name of the district when hovering over the district, a functionality we had already achieved with the previous code

# Adds a legend to the previous map
map_categoricals %>% 
  addLegend(pal = factpal,  # Specify palette
            values = ~name, # Specify variable of mad_districts@data followed
                            # by the palette
            opacity = 1)    # Specify the opacity level of the colors in th

4. Color the polygons following the average prices (continuous variable)

The variable avg_price is a continuous numerical variable that has low and high values. In this case we want a divergent or sequential scale with high avg_prices in red and the rest of the values with appropriate colors to indicate the smaller avg_price. We will see this through some examples.

Lets examine the sequential and divergent scales in the package RColorBrewer.

# Display sequential palettes to pick one among them
display.brewer.all(type = "seq")

# Display sequential palettes to pick one among them
display.brewer.all(type = "div")

Of these scales we are going to try YlOrRd (sequential) and RdYlBu (divergent).

4.1 Palette YlOrRd

Instead of using colorFactor() to build the scale we use colorNumeric(), because now we are dealing with a continuous numerical variable and we want to build a continuous scale of colors (like when we used a gradeint scale in ggplot). The function takes the same arguments:

  • palette: this argument specified the colors to map the data to. It can take one of several forms:
    • The name of a preset palette from the RColorBrewer package, e.g. "RdYlBu", "Accent", or "Greens". These scales can be found on this link. We will also see them how to add to them within R
    • The full name of a viridis palette: "viridis", "magma", "inferno", or "plasma". These can be found on this link
    • A character vector specifying colors, e.g. c("#000000", "#0000FF", "#FFFFFF"), topo.colors(10).
  • domain: tellls the color function the range of input values. We will pass NULL here and the palette function will infer the range everytime we use it in a map.
# Define a scale appropriate for a continuous variable
# with continuous colors.
contpal <- colorNumeric(palette = "YlOrRd", 
                        domain = NULL)

leaflet(mad_districts) %>%
    
    # Loads the background map
    addTiles() %>%
    
    # Loads the polygons
    addPolygons(
      
      # Adds thick line for polygon boundaries
      stroke = TRUE, 
      
      smoothFactor = 0.3,
      
      # Sets width value for polygon boundaries
      weight = 2, 
      
      # Changes default color of boundaries and fill
      color = "white",

      # Dashed pattern to the boundaries
      dashArray = "3",
      
      # Use the previously created color scale to fill the polygons
      # Note that name refers to the column avg_price in mad_districts@data,
      # which signals the average price per square meter in each district.
      fillColor =  ~contpal(avg_price), 
      
      # Adjusts the transparecy of the fill color of the polygons
      fillOpacity = 0.7,
      
      # Shows label when hovering over the districts
      # The variable name referes to the name of the district 
      # to be found in the dataframe mad_districts@data
      label = ~paste0(name, " - ", avg_price, " €/m2"),

      # Adds highlight as the moue hovers over
      highlightOptions = highlightOptions(
        weight = 4,
        color = "grey",
        dashArray = "",
        fillOpacity = 0.7,
        bringToFront = TRUE)
      ) %>% 
  
    addLegend(pal = contpal, 
              values = ~avg_price, 
              opacity = 1.0)

This results looks acceptale. Lets try as well the other proposed scale.

4.2 Palette RdYlBu

Note that we use the argument reverse = TRUE to ensure the colors are assigned properly to the low and high ends of the variable! I tried generating the graph and included reverse when I saw the colors were not properly assigned.

# Define a scale appropriate for a continuous variable
# with continuous colors.
# NOTE THE ARGUMENT reverse = TRUE - to have colors appropriately

contpal <- colorNumeric(palette = "RdYlBu", 
                        domain = NULL,

      fillOpacity = 0.7,
      
      # Shows label when hovering over the districts
      # The variable name referes to the name of the district 
      # to be found in the dataframe mad_districts@data
      label = ~paste0(name, " - ", avg_price, " €/m2"),
  
      # Adds highlight as the moue hovers over
      highlightOptions = highlightOptions(
        weight = 4,
        color = "grey",
        dashArray = "",
        fillOpacity = 0.7,
        bringToFront = TRUE)
      ) %>% 
  
    addLegend(pal = contpal, 
              values = ~avg_price, 
              opacity = 1.0)

This also looks acceptable, but perhaps the lower blues are too dark. We can control this with some effort

4.3 Palette RdYlBu with less intense color endings

The function brewer.pal fron RColorBrewer returns the decimal colors for the scales in RColorBrewer. It returns a vector of Hexadecimal colors.

# n = number of colors
# name = name of the scale
v_colors <- brewer.pal(n = 11, name = 'RdYlBu')
v_colors
 [1] "#A50026" "#D73027" "#F46D43" "#FDAE61" "#FEE090" "#FFFFBF" "#E0F3F8"
 [8] "#ABD9E9" "#74ADD1" "#4575B4" "#313695"

We can then go and visualize those colors with the library scales

scales::show_col(v_colors, 
                 cex_label = 0.4, 
                 ncol = 1,
                 labels = TRUE)

Using rev() we can reverse the vector and flip the colors:

scales::show_col(rev(v_colors), 
                 cex_label = 0.4, 
                 ncol = 1,
                 labels = TRUE)

We want to:

  1. Reduce the number of colors in the scale.
  2. While keeping the midpoint.

We can attain this reducing the colors in steps of 2. Lets try this:

v_colors <- brewer.pal(n = 9, name = 'RdYlBu')
scales::show_col(rev(v_colors), 
                 cex_label = 0.4, 
                 ncol = 1,
                 labels = TRUE)

We can now use this vector of colors to define a scale for our map using color numeric

v_colors <- rev(brewer.pal(9, "RdYlBu"))
contpal <- colorNumeric(palette = v_colors,
                        domain = NULL)

leaflet(mad_districts) %>%
    
    # Loads the background map
    addTiles() %>%
    
    # Loads the polygons
    addPolygons(
      
      # Adds thick line for polygon boundaries
      stroke = TRUE, 
      
      smoothFactor = 0.3,
      
      # Sets width value for polygon boundaries
      weight = 2, 
      
      # Changes default color of boundaries and fill
      color = "white",
      
      # Dashed pattern to the boundaries
      dashArray = "3",
      
      # Use the previously created color scale to fill the polygons
      # Note that name refers to the column avg_price in mad_districts@data,
      # which signals the average price per square meter in each district.
      fillColor =  ~contpal(avg_price), 
      
      # Adjusts the transparecy of the fill color of the polygons
      fillOpacity = 0.7,
      
      # Shows label when hovering over the districts
      # The variable name referes to the name of the district 
      # to be found in the dataframe mad_districts@data
      label = ~paste0(name, " - ", avg_price, " €/m2"),
      
      # Adds highlight as the moue hovers over
      highlightOptions = highlightOptions(
        weight = 4,
        color = "grey",
        dashArray = "",
        fillOpacity = 0.7,
        bringToFront = TRUE)
      ) %>% 
  
    addLegend(pal = contpal, 
              values = ~avg_price, 
              opacity = 1.0)

To my eyes, in this case, the previous result looks better, particularly because it reflects bettwe the high end prices of the district Salamanca.

5. Color the polygons following the average prices (continuous variable) but making it discrete using the quantiles of the variable.

This can be done using the function colorQuantile() to generate a color scale based on the quantiles automatically.

# The variable n specifies the number of quantiles to be generated
qpal <- colorQuantile(palette = "YlOrRd",
                      domain = NULL,
                      n = 8)

leaflet(mad_districts) %>%
    
    # Loads the background map
    addTiles() %>%
    
    # Loads the polygons
    addPolygons(
      
      # Adds thick line for polygon boundaries
      stroke = TRUE, 
      
      smoothFactor = 0.3,
      
      # Sets width value for polygon boundaries
      weight = 2.5, 
      
      # Changes default color of boundaries and fill
      color = "white",
      
      # Dashed pattern to the boundaries
      dashArray = "3",
      
      # Use the previously created color scale to fill the polygons
      # Note that name refers to the column avg_price in mad_districts@data,
      # which signals the average price per square meter in each district.
      fillColor =  ~qpal(avg_price), 
      
      # Adjusts the transparecy of the fill color of the polygons
      fillOpacity = 0.7,
      
      # Shows label when hovering over the districts
      # The variable name referes to the name of the district 
      # to be found in the dataframe mad_districts@data
      label = ~paste0(name, " - ", avg_price, " €/m2"),
  
      # Adds highlight as the moue hovers over
      highlightOptions = highlightOptions(
        weight = 4,
        color = "grey",
        dashArray = "",
        fillOpacity = 0.7,
        bringToFront = TRUE)
      ) %>% 
  
    addLegend(pal = qpal, 
              values = ~avg_price, 
              opacity = 1.0)
